<TITLE>School board gun-shy about seeking tax hike</TITLE>


<TEXT>
By Katie Langford 
<TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="2017-01-28">Saturday</TIMEX3>, <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="2017-01-28">January 28</TIMEX3>, <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="2017">2017</TIMEX3> 
 
District 51 Board of Education members are <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">weighing</EVENT> the school districts dire financial needs against what they perceive as the Mesa County communitys reluctance to further fund education. 
 
That was one of a handful of discussions among board members at a special work <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">session</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE" value="2017-W04">last week</TIMEX3>. 
 
For <TIMEX3 tid="t5" type="DURATION" value="P1Y">more than a year</TIMEX3>, school board members have <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">talked</EVENT> about the need for more funding. They have <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">asked</EVENT> district staff to catalog what needs to be <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">updated</EVENT> and <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">fixed</EVENT>, and board members have <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">visited</EVENT> every school in the district to <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">talk</EVENT> to teachers and staff about their schools needs. 
 
That includes a $58 million <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">list</EVENT> of critical repair needs, as well as security updates, building additions and funding full-day kindergarten. 
 
The school board will <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">make</EVENT> a decision in <TIMEX3 tid="t6" type="DATE" value="FUTURE_REF">coming months</TIMEX3> whether to <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">pursue</EVENT> a bond measure and mill levy override in the <TIMEX3 tid="t7" type="DATE" value="2017-11">November</TIMEX3> election. 
 
But as board members <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">move</EVENT> toward that decision, the school districts <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">failed</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t8" type="DATE" value="2011">2011</TIMEX3> mill levy override attempt is still fresh. The $12.5 million measure was <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">voted</EVENT> down by more than 60 percent of voters. 
 
Board member Greg Mikolai, who was on the board in <TIMEX3 tid="t9" type="DATE" value="2011">2011</TIMEX3>, <EVENT eid="e15" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> he <EVENT eid="e16" class="I_STATE">wants</EVENT> to be <EVENT eid="e17" class="STATE">careful</EVENT> about how the district and school board <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">ask</EVENT> voters for more funding. He <EVENT eid="e19" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> he is wary of repeatedly <EVENT eid="e20" class="I_ACTION">asking</EVENT> for a tax increase when voters have recently <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">voted</EVENT> one down. 
 
Back in <TIMEX3 tid="t10" type="DATE" value="2011">2011</TIMEX3>, we did a poll and we <EVENT eid="e22" class="I_ACTION">heard</EVENT> people <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">liked</EVENT> the idea of this, and they <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">liked</EVENT> the idea of this, but they dont <EVENT eid="e25" class="I_STATE">want</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">pay</EVENT> for it, he <EVENT eid="e27" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>. Thats why we havent even <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">gone</EVENT> forward and <EVENT eid="e29" class="OCCURRENCE">attempted</EVENT> until <TIMEX3 tid="t11" type="DURATION" value="P6Y">six years later</TIMEX3> because we <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">lost</EVENT> so badly. Thats a political reality. 
 
School board members will likely <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">pursue</EVENT> a professional poll to <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">gauge</EVENT> the communitys interest in <EVENT eid="e33" class="OCCURRENCE">increasing</EVENT> taxes to fund schools. 
 
District 51 is also <EVENT eid="e34" class="I_ACTION">applying</EVENT> for the states competitive Building Excellent Schools Today grant in order to <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">replace</EVENT> Orchard Mesa Middle School, a 56-year-old building with a long list of repair needs. 
 
Director of Maintenance Eric Nilsen <EVENT eid="e36" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> the states facility assessor <EVENT eid="e37" class="OCCURRENCE">visited</EVENT> Orchard Mesa <TIMEX3 tid="t12" type="DATE" value="2017-W04">last week</TIMEX3>. 
 
The grant would be for approximately $13 million, but BEST grants are conditional on community support. Even if the district won the grant, if voters didnt <EVENT eid="e38" class="I_STATE">agree</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e39" class="OCCURRENCE">pay</EVENT> for the new school, the school district would not <EVENT eid="e40" class="OCCURRENCE">get</EVENT> the grant money. 
 
Nilsen <EVENT eid="e41" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> a poll or other evidence of public support might be <EVENT eid="e42" class="I_ACTION">needed</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e43" class="OCCURRENCE">win</EVENT> the grant. 
 
When they <EVENT eid="e44" class="I_ACTION">commit</EVENT> that size of a grant they want some confidence that the community is going to <EVENT eid="e45" class="OCCURRENCE">support</EVENT> it, he <EVENT eid="e46" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>.
</TEXT>


